Caesar Cipher Implementation
        A simple Python program to encrypt and decrypt messages using the Caesar cipher algorithm. Supports both encryption (positive shift) and decryption (negative shift).

Features:
Encrypts alphabetic characters by shifting letters forward
Decrypts by shifting letters backward
Preserves non-alphabetic characters (spaces, punctuation)
Interactive command-line interface

Example Usage:

Encrypt "HELLO" with shift 4
text
Enter choice (encrypt / decrypt): encrypt
Enter text: HELLO
Enter shift value: 4
Encrypted text: LIPPS
Decrypt "Jg qh iwtg" with reverse shift (-2)
text
Enter choice (encrypt / decrypt): decrypt
Enter text: Jg qh iwtg
Enter shift value: 2
Decrypted text: He of srpe

Code:
python
def caesar(text, shift):
    result = ""

    for ch in text:
        if ch.isalpha():
            result += chr(ord(ch) + shift)
        else:
            result += ch

    return result

choice = input("Enter choice (encrypt / decrypt): ")
text = input("Enter text: ")
shift = int(input("Enter shift value: "))

if choice == "encrypt":
    print("Encrypted text:", caesar(text, shift))
elif choice == "decrypt":
    print("Decrypted text:", caesar(text, -shift))
else:
    print("Invalid choice! Enter encrypt or decrypt.")


How It Works:
Encryption: Each letter shifts forward by shift positions in the alphabet
Decryption: Each letter shifts backward by shift positions
Non-alphabetic characters remain unchanged


Installation
Copy the code into a file named caesar_cipher.py

Run with python caesar_cipher.py
